I need your help with this ... Please watch this video until the end to see 2 different concepts I designed for the back of our new home (you can pause this video to see both options in detail) - I would love to know which option you like more. I need to place my siding order before the end of the week as we’re getting very close to finishing stucco on the front and sides, and moving scaffolding to the back.⁣
⁣
All three siding profiles shown in the video are Celect Cellular Composit Siding by @royalbuildingproducts - you know how particular I am about the smallest details and this is the only siding I was able to find that eliminates gaps and unattractive seams in between planks with their interlocking joint technology. It looks just like painted wood but without the maintenance. ⁣
⁣
I ordered samples of all three profiles in the exact color I plan on using and will make sure to share them with you tomorrow in stories with all details. I’m definitely using Clapboard profile, I’m just not sure if I should mix it with Shake or Board & Batten. ⁣
⁣

Make sure to watch with sound - this video will show the actual powder room at the new house outlining locations of all fixtures, as well as my design inspiration/color scheme/mood board showing the overall look and feel of how I envision my powder room to look when finished.⁣
⁣
I finalized sizes and locations of all fixtures but haven’t selected any of the finishes just yet except for the wall faucet (I chose Jason Wu faucet by @brizofaucet ) - I had to commit to a faucet now because wall faucets must be installed in-wall during rough plumbing. Everything else will be chosen once I zero in on the perfect wallpaper.⁣
⁣
I know that some of you weren’t sure about this powder room layout but I’m hoping this video will explain how I plan on making it interesting and comfortable. Please do share what you think - I can not wait to read your feedback!⁣

After months of designing and redesigning with my amazing architect Dan @planarchitecture - I’m thrilled to share the final layout of the first floor in my new home!⁣
We should be breaking ground next month but in my mind I’m already living there 🙈 What do you think? What is your favorite part? I’m so excited about the covered outdoor space and my new kitchen! I’ve been living without a dining room for almost two years - I can’t wait to host my first dinner party in this beautiful new home!⁣

node.text:
Hurricane Ida update. Thank you for reaching out and checking up on me. We got very lucky. Our part of New Jersey did not get hit as badly as many other areas you probably saw on the news. No damage to our home, no water in the basement. 

We finished grading and seeding a few days before Ida, and the heavy rain and wind we got Wednesday night washed away some of the top soil and grass seed so this weekend we’ll be cleaning up and re-seeding. Not ideal but it’s nothing compared to what Ida did to other parts of the county. 

Please share how you’re doing if you live in New Jersey or any other state affected by Ida.

node.text:
And we are one step closer to completion! Our deck is finished, now I just need to find the perfect railing.

What I love about our decking material is that it’s unlike anything else out there - it looks just like hardwood floors but requires no maintenance. It’s called Zuri Premium Decking by @royalbuildingproducts and it comes in a variety of colors - we chose Chestnut and I love how it looks against all the greenery in our backyard :)

Thank you very much for all of your votes about our staircase balusters I shared last week - these black iron balusters won by a landslide and now this rendering shows how they’re going to look with the rest of the finishes in our new foyer!

While reading your comments I noticed that quite a few of you suggested to not paint our staircase risers white (as shown in the rendering), and instead stain the entire staircase to match our pre-finished wood floors. I shared a few example photos of both options in today’s stories and now that you see this rendering of the entire foyer, do you think the staircase would look better with stained or painted risers? I usually prefer white risers, but don’t hate the idea of stained risers in this case. Very curious to know how you feel about this.

node.text:
Wall sconces or pendants over the island? Or both? Part of me wants to do both, but I don’t want this kitchen to look too busy that’s why my original design calls for sconces only (swipe left to see rendering)

We will have recessed lights in the ceiling and we are pre-wired for pendants if I’ll decide to add them. I’ve been looking at sconces and pendants for this kitchen for close to two years and I’m still having a hard time finding the perfect pieces. Lighting is an incredibly important design element as different shapes and styles could take the overall look of a space in so many different directions.

This photo was taken during our countertops installation about two months ago but not much has changed since then in the kitchen as we’re still waiting for deliveries of appliances, faucets, interior doors and other materials. As many of you probably know most building materials and furnishings are taking much longer than usual to get these days and it looks like I tend to like products with extra long lead times. Lighting is the only thing that hasn’t been ordered for this kitchen yet but I know I will eventually find those perfect pieces that will speak to me …

Last week I watched Q&A stories of an interior designer whose work I love. There were several questions asked about design pet peeves and things to avoid when designing or building a home, but all of them were answered with “I don’t want to say because I don’t want to hurt anyone’s feelings” 

Those answers got me thinking …. Whether it’s something positive or negative I always answer those types of questions honestly based on my knowledge and experience in hopes that my answers would prevent someone else from making a mistake. 

All design and construction projects take a long time and are expensive, and there’s nothing worse than building something one way, only to later learn that it could have been  done a better way - I’ve been there myself many times before as I started designing and building homes almost 15 years ago, when we didn’t have as much access to information as we do today.

I will be honest - it never occurred to me that talking about something that I regretted doing in my own projects, or something I wouldn’t want to do (while explaining my reasons why) could hurt someone’s feelings, because I myself never take anything I see online personally, and I really enjoy learning what other designers and homeowners like and don’t like when it comes to homes. But I also realize that I must have thicker skin than most people because I have been sharing my life publicly online for close to a decade. 

This has been on my mind for a few days now and instead of spending more time trying to figure out if I should be filtering what I share, or continue to share as usual, I wanted to see how you feel about this

We’re in a little dilemma about the floor of our portico and I would love to know what you would do in this situation … What kind of material do you have installed on the floor of your front porch or portico? I’ve always envisioned clean, smooth, grey and seamless surface (swipe left to see our rendering) so I was thinking of going with concrete, but when I shared that plan with my contractor he was strongly against it. My contractor works on many beautiful custom homes and he said that most of his clients go for bluestone, granite, tile, pavers - pretty much anything but NOT concrete. I like the idea of concrete because I would like for the floor in that area to have a clean, simple and seamless look and I’m afraid that installing stone would make it look too busy. My contractor feels that concrete floor in that area would cheapen the look of the entire house. 

Am I the only person who likes the idea of concrete on the floor of the portico? What kind of material do you have installed on the floor outside of your front door? how do you like it? and what would you do in this situation?
